These teams have both (i) p-values below 0.05 and (ii) mean home scores that are substantially higher than mean away scores. This provides statistical evidence of a home-field advantage in scoring for those teams.

For a few other teams (e.g., WAS and ARI), the p-values are relatively close to 0.05 (e.g., 0.1621 and 0.06047 respectively). Although these are not statistically significant, they may suggest a weak trend and could become significant with more data.


## Conclusion

The results suggest that home-field advantage in goal scoring is not universal across the league. Only a few teams (such as ATL, TEN, PHI, and DAL) show a statistically significant increase in scoring at home, while for most teams the venue does not appear to influence scoring performance.
